{"parse":{"title":"Montague Fordham","pageid":19760693,"revid":840267538,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>Montague Edward Fordham</b> (1864\u20131948) was an <a href=\"/wiki/England\" title=\"England\">English</a> agriculturalist and advocate of rural reform. He belonged to the <a href=\"/wiki/Religious_Society_of_Friends\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Religious Society of Friends\">Religious Society of Friends</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> and was a historian and barrister and by profession.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Con1_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Con1-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Fordham first gained notability in <a href=\"/wiki/Birmingham\" title=\"Birmingham\">Birmingham</a> where he was involved in a number of initiatives in support of traditional <a href=\"/wiki/Handicraft\" title=\"Handicraft\">handicraft</a>. To this end, he was the first director of the <a href=\"/wiki/Birmingham_Guild_and_School_of_Handicrafts\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Birmingham Guild and School of Handicrafts\">Birmingham Guild and School of Handicrafts</a> following its 1890 foundation,<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> as well as serving as the director of the Arts and Craft Gallery from 1899 to 1908 and head of the Artificers Guild from 1903 to 1906.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>Fordham's main passion, however, was rural reform, and he formed the Land Club Union in 1908 which aimed to establish model farms, organise farmers' banks and loans, provide machinery, and revive traditional life and festivals in the country.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Con1_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Con1-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> The following year, he published <i>Mother Earth: A Proposal for the Permanent Reconstruction of our Country Life</i> as an effective manifesto for the Union, with a foreword by <a href=\"/wiki/John_A._Hobson\" title=\"John A. Hobson\">John A. Hobson</a>. The book attacked what he saw as the anti-farmer nature of the economic system; it also anticipated the modern <a href=\"/wiki/Organic_movement\" title=\"Organic movement\">organic movement</a> by attacking modern methods.<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> After the publication of this book, he became involved with a number of rural reform groups, such as the Agricultural Organisation Society and Land Clubs League, arguing in favour of his desire to see a return to small-holdings.<sup id=\"cite_ref-barb_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-barb-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> He desired <a href=\"/wiki/Autarky\" title=\"Autarky\">autarky</a> in food production for all countries, while also highlighting the dangers of <a href=\"/wiki/Soil_erosion\" title=\"Soil erosion\">soil erosion</a> caused by the concentration of agriculture in certain countries.<sup id=\"cite_ref-barb_6-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-barb-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>His 1924 book <i>The Rebuilding of Rural England</i> contained an attack on the existing monetary systems, and argued instead in favour of making money available as credit, thus indicating a link with <a href=\"/wiki/Social_Credit\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Social Credit\">Social Credit</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Con2_7-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Con2-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup> His criticisms of the economic system of Britain became more marked after the 1931 slump.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Con2_7-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Con2-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>He established the <a href=\"/wiki/Rural_Reconstruction_Association\" title=\"Rural Reconstruction Association\">Rural Reconstruction Association</a> in 1926 and served as its Council Secretary for 20 years, with the group at the forefront of the agricultural reform movement.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Con2_7-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Con2-7\">&#91;7&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>His son <a href=\"/wiki/Michael_Fordham\" title=\"Michael Fordham\">Michael Fordham</a> became a noted <a href=\"/wiki/Psychiatrist\" title=\"Psychiatrist\">psychiatrist</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-8\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-8\">&#91;8&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Montague_Fordham&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">G. Macklin, <i>Very Deeply Dyed in Black</i>, New York: IB Tauris, 2007, p. 66</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Con1-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Con1_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Con1_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">P. Conford, 'Finance versus Farming: Rural Reconstruction and Economic Reform 1894-1955', <i>Rural History</i>, 2002, Vol.13, No.2 ,p. 228</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://palimpsest.stanford.edu/byform/mailing-lists/exlibris/2005/03/msg00131.html\">Re: Birmingham Guild of Handicraft</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.styles-silver.co.uk/acatalog/Artificers_Guild.html\">Edward Spencer and the Artificers Guild</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Conford, 'Finance versus Farming', pp. 228-9</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-barb-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-barb_6-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-barb_6-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Peter Barberis, John McHugh, Mike Tyldesley, <i>Encyclopedia of British and Irish Political Organizations</i>, 2002, p. 32</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Con2-7\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Con2_7-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Con2_7-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Con2_7-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Conford, 'Finance versus Farming', p. 229</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-8\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-8\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_19950425/ai_n13978895\">Michael Fordham obituary</a></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1238\nCached time: 20180904071352\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.040 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.048 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 185/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 332/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 80/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 7/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 3467/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 0/400\nLua time usage: 0.003/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 525 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n10